Since you are a Senior Software Engineer with a passion for motorcycles and an active YouTube channel, let’s explain Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) using a real-world Motorcycle Management System as the context.1. Class & ObjectA Class is a blueprint (the technical specifications of a motorcycle), and an Object is the physical manifestation (the actual bike parked in your garage).Pythonclass Motorcycle:
    def __init__(self, brand, model):
        self.brand = brand
        self.model = model

    def start_engine(self):
        print(f"The {self.brand} {self.model} engine is idling...")

# Creating an Object
my_bike = Motorcycle("Husqvarna", "Svartpilen 250")
my_bike.start_engine()
2. InheritanceInheritance allows a class to derive attributes and methods from another class. This is perfect for categorizing different types of bikes.Real-time Scenario: An AdventureBike is a type of Motorcycle but with extra features like higher ground clearance.Pythonclass AdventureBike(Motorcycle):
    def __init__(self, brand, model, ground_clearance):
        super().__init__(brand, model)  # Inherit brand and model
        self.ground_clearance = ground_clearance

    def go_offroad(self):
        print(f"Navigating rocks with {self.ground_clearance}mm clearance!")

adv_bike = AdventureBike("KTM", "390 Adventure", 200)
adv_bike.start_engine()  # Inherited method
adv_bike.go_offroad()   # Specific method
3. EncapsulationEncapsulation wraps data (attributes) and methods into a single unit and restricts access to the inner workings. We use a single underscore _ (protected) or double underscore __ (private) to hide sensitive data.Real-time Scenario: A rider shouldn't be able to manually change the Odometer reading directly; it should only be updated by the system as you ride.Pythonclass Dashboard:
    def __init__(self):
        self.__odometer = 5000  # Private attribute

    def drive(self, kms):
        if kms > 0:
            self.__odometer += kms
            print(f"Odometer updated: {self.__odometer} km")

    def get_reading(self):
        return self.__odometer

my_dash = Dashboard()
my_dash.drive(150)
# print(my_dash.__odometer)  # This would raise an AttributeError
4. PolymorphismPolymorphism allows different classes to have methods with the same name but different behaviors. "Poly" means many, and "morph" means forms.Real-time Scenario: Different bikes have different exhaust notes. You call sound(), but the result depends on the bike.Pythonclass Svartpilen:
    def exhaust_note(self):
        return "Crisp Thump"

class Himalayan:
    def exhaust_note(self):
        return "Deep Grumble"

def play_sound(bike_obj):
    print(bike_obj.exhaust_note())

play_sound(Svartpilen())
play_sound(Himalayan())
5. AbstractionAbstraction hides complex implementation details and only shows the necessary features to the user. In Python, we use the abc module to create Abstract Base Classes.Real-time Scenario: Every braking system must have a brake() method, but the "how" (Disc vs. Drum) is hidden from the rider who just pulls the lever.Pythonfrom abc import ABC, abstractmethod

class BrakingSystem(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def apply_brake(self):
        pass

class DiscBrake(BrakingSystem):
    def apply_brake(self):
        print("Applying hydraulic pressure to calipers.")

class DrumBrake(BrakingSystem):
    def apply_brake(self):
        print("Expanding brake shoes against the drum.")

# my_brake = BrakingSystem() # This would raise an error (cannot instantiate abstract class)
front_brake = DiscBrake()
front_brake.apply_brake()
